g and making, in playwrights from Aeschylus, Marlowe, Shakespeare, and Milton to Beckett, Arthur Miller, and Sarah Kane. Richard Halpern places these figures in conversation with works by Aristotle, Smith, Hegel, Marx, Hannah Arendt, Georges Bataille, and others in order to trace the long history of the ways in which economic thought and tragic drama interact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEconomics in literature. 0aTragedy - Themes, motives. 0aTragedyxHistory and criticism. 0aTragedyxThemes, motives. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aaction.  adrama.  aeconomics.  aphilosophy.  apolitical economy.  apolitics.  asociety.  atheater.  atragedy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022643365340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226433790423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226433790/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles